<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Characteristic Species</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Purshia</i> <i>stansburiana</i> is dominant or co-dominant in the shrub canopy with <i>Agave</i> <i>utahensis</i>, <i>Artemisia</i> <i>nova</i>, <i>Artemisia</i> <i>tridentata</i>, <i>Coleogyne</i> <i>ramosissima</i>, <i>Ephedra</i> <i>viridis</i>, <i>Ericameria</i> <i>nauseosa</i>, <i>Mortonia</i> <i>utahensis</i>, <i>Opuntia</i> <i>chlorotica</i>, <i>Prunus</i> <i>fasciculata</i>, <i>Salvia</i> <i>mohavensis</i>, <i>Thamnosma</i> <i>montana</i> and <i>Yucca</i> <i>baccata</i>. Emergent trees may be present at low cover, including <i>Juniperus</i> <i>osteosperma</i> or <i>Pinus</i> <i>monophylla</i>. </div>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Vegetation Layers</h4>
	<div class="text">  Shrubs < 5 m; canopy is open. Herbaceous layer is sparse to open. </div>
</div>

        
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Membership Rules</h4>
	<ul class="text">
		
		<li><i>Purshia stansburiana</i> ≥ 2% absolute cover in the shrub canopy, no other single species with greater cover (Thomas et al. 2004).</li>
		
		<li><i>Mortonia utahensis</i> ≥ 2% absolute cover in the shrub canopy, and dominant or co-dominant with other shrubs (Evens et al. 2014).</li>
		
		<li><i>Purshia stansburiana</i> ≥ 2% absolute cover in the shrub canopy, and dominant or co-dominant with other shrubs (Evens et al. 2014).</li>
		
	</ul>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Habitats</h4>
	<div class="text"> Edges of intermittent watercourses, canyons, hills, mountains, moderate-steep slopes, and cliffs. Soils are well drained, shallow,  bedrock or rocky, rapidly permeable, and usually calcareous.  </div>
</div>

        
