<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Purshia stansburiana </i>is a relatively long-lived shrub that typically reproduces by seed. Wind and animals disperse the seeds, and animals cache them. Seeds require cold stratification, and remain viable up to 15 years. Seedling establishment is highest in years of below-average precipitation on open, disturbed sites. Thatch of non-native grasses prevents seedling establishment. Recruitment in some parts of its range is sporadic and limited (Howard 1995, Reid et al. 1999). <i>Cowania stansburiana, Purshia mexicana, </i>and <i>Purshia mexicana </i>var. <i>stansburiana </i>are other names used for this plant. <br/>
<br/>
The alliance in California is restricted to mountains of the eastern Mojave Desert and adjacent Great Basin. It occurs in small, scattered stands on relatively steep slopes, which are often adjacent to <i>Pinus monophylla </i>stands or <i>Artemisia tridentata </i>or <i>Purshia tridentata </i>shrublands. Virtually all stands observed occur on limestone or marble. Disturbance from flooding is likely in the canyon bottom stands. The vegetation type of <i>Mortonia utahensis</i> previously was placed in its own "alliance" or special stands (Thomas et al. 2004); but because it is ecologically overlapping in species composition and environmental characteristics with stands of <i>Purshia stansburiana </i>, it has been moved to this alliance. </div>
</div>

    
	
	
